## TypeScript Types
> Always import from `@/types` — never redefine types inline

```typescript
// types/index.ts

export type Role = 'user' | 'assistant'

export interface Message {
  id: string
  role: Role
  content: string
  createdAt: string
}

export interface User {
  id: string
  email: string
  username: string
}

export interface AuthResponse {
  accessToken: string
  user: User
}

export interface ChatSession {
  id: string
  title: string
  createdAt: string
}
```

---

## Tailwind CSS 4 Rules
> CRITICAL — Tailwind 4 syntax is different from v3

```css
/* globals.css — use this exact syntax */
@import "tailwindcss";
```

NEVER use the old v3 syntax:
```css
/* WRONG — do not use this */
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
```

- Use Tailwind utility classes only — no inline styles, no CSS modules
- Dark mode class: `dark:` prefix works as normal
- Custom colors go in `@theme` block inside globals.css if needed

---

## Next.js 16 App Router Rules

### Server vs Client components
- Every component is a Server Component by default — do NOT add `"use client"` unless needed
- Add `"use client"` ONLY when the component uses:
  - `useState`, `useEffect`, `useReducer`, `useRef` or any hook
  - Event handlers like `onClick`, `onChange`, `onSubmit`
  - Browser APIs (`localStorage`, `window`, `document`)
  - The `useAuth` hook

### Routing
- `app/(auth)/login/page.tsx` — the `(auth)` folder is a route group, does NOT appear in URL
- `app/chat/page.tsx` — protected, redirects to `/login` if no token
- `app/page.tsx` — root page, just redirects to `/login`

### Data fetching
- Server Components fetch data directly (no useEffect)
- Client Components use `useState` + `useEffect` for data that changes

